          Thegeneralcourseoftheinvestigation:"The general course of the investigation",
          Thegeneralcourseoftheinvestigationto:"In the 2025 academic year, we conducted a study aimed at examining the level of stress among students of different age groups. The goal of our research was to identify the factors that influence the development of stress reactions among students. Through our observations and analysis, we noticed that age has a direct impact on the manifestation of stress. The process of transitioning from one grade to another increases the level of anxiety and emotional tension among students. As students enter middle school, their social environment undergoes significant changes. They face a range of changes in their social environment, including the replacement of teachers, the introduction of new subjects, and the implementation of a classroom system. The form of communication with teachers changes: they become stricter and more demanding, and there is no emotional connection like with a class teacher in elementary school. Middle school is considered a transitional period, as it lies between childhood and adolescence. At this age, hormonal changes occur, and puberty begins. There are also changes in the educational process.",
          fivethgraderesults:"5th grade results",
          fivethgraderesultsto:"See diagram 1",
          fivethgraderesultstoo:"The results of the survey showed that among fifth-grade students, when asked How often do you worry?, most students (54%) chose the option sometimes, 19% - often, 21% - rarely and only 6% - never. According to the results, it can be concluded that fifth-graders regularly experience stress, but its level does not reach constant emotional tension. Most often, the cause of stress was study and evaluation: tests and control works - 29%, bad grades - 29%. The results indicate that the main factors causing stress in schoolchildren are the fear of mistakes and social pressure. One of the most common reactions to a stressful situation is rapid heartbeat (30%) and fear (21%). Less common reactions are anger (8%), the desire to cry (13%), abdominal pain and headache (9%), trembling in the body were chosen by 3% of students. Due to their age, fifth graders do not always understand what is happening to them. It is difficult for children to connect physical sensations with emotions.",
          seventhgraderesults:"7th grade results",
          seventhgraderesultsto:"See diagram 2",
          seventhgraderesultstoo:"When asked how often students experience stress, the majority of seventh-graders (46%) chose the option often. Another 18% answered sometimes and rarely, while 19% chose almost never. Based on these data, it can be concluded that, unlike in elementary school, stress is more frequent in middle school. Similar to elementary school, frequent stressors include tests (35%) and poor grades (35%). Less common are stressful situations related to answering at the blackboard (23%) and communicating with classmates (6%). Thus, the stress of seventh-graders is mainly related to academic workload. The most common reaction to stressful situations is increased heart rate (28%). Sadness and withdrawal are also common (22%). Headaches and abdominal pain (12%), anger (9%), and shortness of breath (8%) are the least common. The high percentage of those who dont feel anythin indicates emotional immaturity. When asked about how students cope with stress",
          tenthgraderesults:"10th grade results",
          tenthgraderesultsto:"See diagram 3",
          tenthgraderesultstoo:"More than half of tenth-grade students experience stress often or sometimes (31%). Another 21% chose the rarely option, and only 17% reported that they never experience stress, indicating that one in three students regularly faces stress. The main causes of stress for high school students include tests and quizzes (51%), class presentations (21%), and, less frequently, poor grades (15%) and difficulties in socializing with classmates (13%). The most common reactions are heart palpitations (27%), sadness and detachment (20%), aggression (18%), and difficulty breathing (17%) and no symptoms (18%) are less common. Most students (38%) prefer to withdraw and spend time alone, 28% share with friends, and only 6% turn to adults. Communication (25%) is the primary way to reduce stress, with music and games (14%), food, and sports as secondary methods (12%). High school students also consult a psychologist (2%) and practice breathing exercises.",

          //* 2 section
          Conclusion:"Conclusion",
